+{"type":"message","id":"532d07c6","parentId":"505303f5","timestamp":"2026-03-28T18:37:01.313Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Operator notes for this run:\n## Operator note — 2026-03-28T18:27:01.073Z\n\nRefer to health-check/health-check.txt and address\n\nThese notes are authoritative user steering for this run. Follow them unless they directly conflict with the repository state or the controller's explicit task.\n\nParent conversation handoff summary:\nParent conversation handoff summary\nSummary model: anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5\nSource items: 265\n\nOverview:\nST6 is an enterprise software company enabling weekly commit-based planning with AI assistance. The session discussed how to make AI integral to the product (not bolted-on) and reviewed an evaluation pipeline for AI quality. We concluded the next milestone is implementing enforceable AI quality thresholds via: adding a critical field to eval cases, wiring two existing LLM judge prompts (title-quality, criteria-quality) into the PromptEvalRunner, committing the most recent eval run as a regression baseline, creating an eval-thresholds.json config, building a Node.js enforcement script that compares results against thresholds and baseline, and integrating that into CI.\n\nSettled decisions:\n- Judge thresholds must be 3-layer: deterministic gates first (schema+case pass rate), LLM judge absolute thresholds second, regression relative thresholds third.\n- Split judge thresholds by risk: high-stakes features (risk signals, insights, RAG) get stricter thresholds (faithfulness >= 0.90) than assistive features (draft, lint, suggestions) which get more permissive thresholds (faithfulness >= 0.85).\n- Deterministic thresholds are hard-gates that block CI; judge and regression thresholds initially soft-gate (report but don't block) until stable.\n- Use eval-baseline.json as regression anchor committed to the repo. When eval runs, the enforcement script compares the latest results to both